Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer State
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Lexer cursor structure: holds the source string plus a position cursor and
human-readable line/column counters. Tracking line and column separately
from byte position lets diagnostics report VHDL source coordinates without
re-scanning, and lets multi-character escapes (newline) update both
counters atomically. Source length is cached because length-of-string is
otherwise computed by scanning to NUL.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
40-byte record (5 x i64): source pointer (offset 0), byte position
(offset 8), 1-based line counter (offset 16, starts at 1), 1-based
column counter (offset 24, starts at 1), cached source length in bytes
(offset 32). All fields are mutated in place by advance/peek as the
lexer walks the source.
@End Implementation

Type called "VHDLLexer":
    source as Integer           Note: Source code string
    position as Integer         Note: Current position in source
    line as Integer             Note: Current line number
    column as Integer           Note: Current column number
    source_length as Integer    Note: Length of source
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Constructs the VHDLLexer cursor in a single 40-byte heap allocation. The
source string is aliased (not copied) so the caller retains ownership of
the source buffer; the lexer's lifetime must therefore be strictly less
than the source string's. Initialising line and column to 1 (not 0)
matches VHDL diagnostics conventions where the first line and column
are numbered 1.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Single allocate call for the 40-byte struct, OOM short-circuit to 0,
then string_length is invoked once to cache source_length at offset 32.
Position starts at 0, line at 1, column at 1, source pointer aliased
at offset 0. No companion destroy_lexer exists — the lexer is owned
by its caller and freed via Layout's deallocate.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_lexer" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create VHDL lexer

    Let lexer_size be 40
    Let lexer be proc allocate from Layout with lexer_size

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let source_len be proc string_length from StringCore with source

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0, source
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, source_len

    Return lexer
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Classification
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
ASCII letter test, used as the lead-character classifier for VHDL
identifiers. VHDL identifiers must start with a letter (per LRM 13.3.1
basic_identifier ::= letter { [ underline ] letter_or_digit }), so this
test is the gate that distinguishes identifier-or-keyword from number,
operator, or punctuation in the dispatch.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Two range checks against ASCII codepoints: uppercase 65..90 (A-Z) and
lowercase 97..122 (a-z). No locale handling — VHDL identifiers are
strictly ASCII in the base language. Returns 1 for letter, 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_letter" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is letter (A-Z, a-z)

    If ch is greater than or equal to 65:
        If ch is less than or equal to 90:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    If ch is greater than or equal to 97:
        If ch is less than or equal to 122:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
ASCII digit test. Used both to start integer/real literal scans and to
continue identifier scans after the first letter (VHDL identifiers
allow digits after the first character).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Single range check 48..57 (ASCII '0' through '9'). Returns 1 for digit,
0 otherwise. No support for non-ASCII or fullwidth digits — VHDL spec
restricts numeric literals to ASCII.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_digit" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is digit (0-9)

    If ch is greater than or equal to 48:
        If ch is less than or equal to 57:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Tests for a hex digit needed inside based literals like 16#FF# where the
base is 16 and the digits can include A-F. The lexer treats the digits
permissively (both upper and lower case) — semantic validation of base
versus actual digit values happens later, not at lex time.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Composed test: defer to is_digit first (0-9), then check uppercase
A-F (65..70) and lowercase a-f (97..102). Returns 1 on any match,
0 otherwise. Three branches because Runa lacks a short-circuit OR
combinator on integer comparisons in this position.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_hex_digit" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is hexadecimal digit (0-9, A-F, a-f)

    If proc is_digit with ch is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    If ch is greater than or equal to 65:
        If ch is less than or equal to 70:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    If ch is greater than or equal to 97:
        If ch is less than or equal to 102:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Whitespace classifier covering the four characters VHDL treats as
insignificant separators: space, tab, LF, CR. Used by skip_whitespace
between tokens. Newlines additionally trigger column reset inside
advance, but at classification level they're just whitespace.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Four equality checks against ASCII codepoints 32 (space), 9 (tab),
10 (LF), 13 (CR). Returns 1 on any match, 0 otherwise. No form-feed
or vertical-tab handling — VHDL LRM only mandates the four listed.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_whitespace" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is whitespace

    If ch is equal to 32:
        Return 1
    End If

    If ch is equal to 9:
        Return 1
    End If

    If ch is equal to 10:
        Return 1
    End If

    If ch is equal to 13:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
ASCII-only lowercase folder. VHDL keywords and identifiers are
case-insensitive (LRM 13.3), so the lexer canonicalises tokens to
lowercase before keyword matching. This helper is the single point
of case conversion for the lexer; using string_to_lower from
StringCore at the token level avoids per-character folding inside
the hot scan loops.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If the character is in 65..90 (uppercase A-Z) returns ch + 32 (the
ASCII case-bit toggle). Anything else is returned unchanged — digits,
underscores, and already-lowercase letters all pass through.
Non-ASCII letters are not folded; they shouldn't appear in standard
VHDL identifiers.
@End Implementation

Process called "to_lowercase" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Convert character to lowercase

    If ch is greater than or equal to 65:
        If ch is less than or equal to 90:
            Return ch plus 32
        End If
    End If

    Return ch
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer Utilities
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Reads the byte at the current cursor without advancing. Returning 0 at
EOF lets callers treat NUL/EOF identically — every scan loop has a
"ch == 0" exit branch that handles both "ran off the end" and the rare
embedded NUL byte. This conflation is safe because VHDL source must
not contain embedded NULs.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads position (offset 8), source (offset 0), source_length (offset 32)
in that order, EOF-guards by comparing pos >= source_len. On valid
position invokes string_char_at from StringCore for the indexed byte.
No bounds-safety beyond the length compare; underlying string is
assumed to be at least source_length bytes valid.
@End Implementation

Process called "peek" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek at current character without advancing

    Let pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let source_len be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    If pos is greater than or equal to source_len:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, pos
    Return ch
End Process

@Reasoning:
Consumes one byte from the source stream and returns it. The dual
duty (read + advance) is intentional: VHDL's hot scan loops want a
single call that both decides "next char" and "make progress" so that
forgetting one is a bug visible immediately as an infinite loop. On
newline, line counter increments and column resets to 1 so subsequent
diagnostics report the correct row.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Pulls pos (8), source (0), len (32), col (24) up-front, EOF-guards
on pos >= len returning 0 without mutating state. Reads the char via
string_char_at, post-increments pos and col, writes both back. The
newline branch checks for LF (10); on LF it loads line from offset 16,
increments, stores back, and overwrites column with 1 (NOT col+1 —
the previous increment is intentionally squashed by the reset).
@End Implementation

Process called "advance" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Advance position and return current character

    Let pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let source_len be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
    Let col be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24

    If pos is greater than or equal to source_len:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, pos

    Set pos to pos plus 1
    Set col to col plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, pos
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, col

    Note: Handle newlines
    If ch is equal to 10:
        Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
        Set line to line plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, line
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, 1
    End If

    Return ch
End Process

@Reasoning:
Drives the cursor past contiguous whitespace before next_token decides
what to scan. Whitespace must be consumed atomically rather than left
for the dispatcher because some VHDL tokens (e.g., the `<` vs `<=`
disambiguation) require lookahead immediately on a non-whitespace byte.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Unbounded `While 1 is equal to 1` loop with two exit conditions: peek
returning 0 (EOF) and is_whitespace returning 0 (non-WS byte). Every
iteration that doesn't exit calls advance which itself handles newline
bookkeeping. Returns 1 unconditionally on exit — there is no failure
path because exceeding EOF is not an error here.
@End Implementation

Process called "skip_whitespace" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip whitespace characters

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let ch be proc peek from lexer

        If ch is equal to 0:
            Return 1
        End If

        If proc is_whitespace with ch is equal to 0:
            Return 1
        End If

        proc advance from lexer
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Consumes a VHDL line comment which begins with `--` and runs to the end
of line (LRM 13.8). Block comments do not exist in VHDL-93; VHDL-2008's
`/* */` form is intentionally NOT supported here — this lexer targets
the common subset and would need a separate handler if block comments
are added later.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Two unconditional advance calls consume the leading `--` (caller has
already confirmed the pair via peek and peek_ahead). Then loops with
peek, exiting on EOF (ch == 0) or newline (LF == 10). The terminating
newline itself is NOT consumed here — skip_whitespace will eat it on
the next call, which is correct because the LF triggers line counter
increment on its own pass.
@End Implementation

Process called "skip_comment" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip single-line comment (-- to end of line)

    Note: Skip the -- characters
    proc advance from lexer
    proc advance from lexer

    Note: Skip until newline
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let ch be proc peek from lexer

        If ch is equal to 0:
            Return 1
        End If

        If ch is equal to 10:
            Return 1
        End If

        proc advance from lexer
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Allocates the uniform 32-byte token record used everywhere downstream.
Putting all four fields at fixed offsets means the parser can read them
without any tag-based shape variation, which is faster than carrying
a separate field-table per token kind.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Single allocate call for 32 bytes (4 x i64). Layout: token_type at
offset 0, value (string pointer or literal payload) at offset 8, line
at offset 16, column at offset 24. OOM short-circuits to 0; callers
must check for null before reading offsets. The value pointer is
aliased — no copy is made.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_token" takes token_type as Integer, value as Integer, line as Integer, column as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create token

    Let token_size be 32
    Let token be proc allocate from Layout with token_size

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 0, token_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 8, value
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 16, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 24, column

    Return token
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Keyword Recognition
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Resolves a scanned identifier against the VHDL keyword set. VHDL has
~80 reserved words spanning design-unit headers (entity, architecture),
declarations (signal, variable), control flow (if, when, loop), logical
and shift operators (and, sll), and common types (std_logic, integer).
This single dispatch keeps the lexer's keyword table linear-string but
correctness-stable: adding new keywords only requires extending this
function.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
First step folds the input to lowercase via string_to_lower (VHDL is
case-insensitive). Each subsequent block tests one keyword via
string_equals; on match returns the corresponding TOKEN_* constant.
The order of the tests is purely logical-grouping (design units,
declarations, port modes, control flow, structural, logical operators,
shift operators, special keywords, type keywords, record/array); it
does not reflect frequency, so future optimisation could reorder for
hot-keyword first matching. Falls through to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER if no
keyword matches — the caller stores the original-case spelling in the
token's value field, preserving user formatting for diagnostics.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Linear scan over ~80 keywords per identifier is acceptable for HIR
translation throughput but would dominate full-source-lex profiles.
A perfect hash or trie keyed on the first 1-3 characters would cut
the average comparison count by an order of magnitude; defer until
profiling shows this as a bottleneck.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "match_keyword" takes word as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Match identifier to keyword (case-insensitive)

    Let word_lower be proc string_to_lower from StringCore with word

    Note: Design Units
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "entity" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_ENTITY
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "architecture" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_ARCHITECTURE
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "configuration" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_CONFIGURATION
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "package" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_PACKAGE
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "library" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_LIBRARY
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "use" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_USE
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "component" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_COMPONENT
    End If

    Note: Declarations
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "signal" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_SIGNAL
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "variable" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_VARIABLE
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "constant" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_CONSTANT
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "type" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_TYPE
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "subtype" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_SUBTYPE
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "generic" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_GENERIC
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "port" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_PORT
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "alias" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_ALIAS
    End If

    Note: Port Modes
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "in" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_IN
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "out" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_OUT
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "inout" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_INOUT
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "buffer" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_BUFFER
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "linkage" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_LINKAGE
    End If

    Note: Control Flow
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "if" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_IF
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "then" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_THEN
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "else" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_ELSE
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "elsif" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_ELSIF
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "case" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_CASE
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "when" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_WHEN
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "loop" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_LOOP
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "for" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_FOR
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "while" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_WHILE
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "exit" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_EXIT
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "next" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_NEXT
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "return" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_RETURN
    End If

    Note: Structural
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "begin" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_BEGIN
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "end" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_END
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "process" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_PROCESS
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "procedure" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_PROCEDURE
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "function" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_FUNCTION
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "is" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_IS
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "of" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_OF
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "to" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_TO
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "downto" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_DOWNTO
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "generate" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_GENERATE
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "block" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_BLOCK
    End If

    Note: Logical Operators
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "and" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_AND
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "or" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_OR
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "not" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_NOT
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "xor" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_XOR
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "nand" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_NAND
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "nor" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_NOR
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "xnor" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_XNOR
    End If

    Note: Shift Operators
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "sll" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_SLL
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "srl" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_SRL
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "sla" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_SLA
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "sra" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_SRA
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "rol" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_ROL
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "ror" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_ROR
    End If

    Note: Special Keywords
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "wait" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_WAIT
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "until" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_UNTIL
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "after" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_AFTER
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "assert" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_ASSERT
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "report" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_REPORT
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "severity" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_SEVERITY
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "others" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_OTHERS
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "null" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_NULL
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "map" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_MAP
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "all" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_ALL
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "range" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_RANGE
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "open" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_OPEN
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "with" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_WITH
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "select" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_SELECT
    End If

    Note: Common Type Keywords
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "std_logic" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_STD_LOGIC
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "std_logic_vector" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_STD_LOGIC_VECTOR
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "integer" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_INTEGER
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "natural" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_NATURAL
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "positive" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_POSITIVE
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "real" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_REAL
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "boolean" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_BOOLEAN
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "bit" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_BIT
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "bit_vector" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_BIT_VECTOR
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "character" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_CHARACTER
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "string" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_STRING
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "time" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_TIME
    End If

    Note: Record and Array
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "record" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_RECORD
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "array" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_ARRAY
    End If

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with word_lower, "access" is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_ACCESS
    End If

    Note: Not a keyword, return identifier
    Return TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Scanning
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Scans a maximal-munch VHDL identifier (letter followed by letter, digit,
or underscore per LRM 13.3.1). The lexer has already confirmed the first
byte is a letter so this routine begins by capturing the start position
and then accumulates while the predicate stays true. Identifier
recognition and keyword classification are fused: once the lexeme is
isolated, match_keyword decides whether to return a reserved-word token
or TOKEN_IDENTIFIER.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Captures start_pos (offset 8), line (16), column (24) on entry. The
main loop peeks each byte and exits on either EOF (ch == 0) or first
non-identifier byte. Underscore (ASCII 95) is treated specially because
is_letter and is_digit both return 0 for it; the three nested If checks
mean "exit if NOT letter AND NOT digit AND NOT underscore". On exit
collects the substring via string_substring, runs match_keyword to get
the token_type (TOKEN_IDENTIFIER if not a keyword), and constructs the
token with start-position line/column for diagnostics.
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_identifier" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan identifier or keyword

    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24

    Note: Scan identifier characters (letter, digit, underscore)
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let ch be proc peek from lexer

        If ch is equal to 0:
            Let end_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
            Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
            Let ident be proc string_substring from StringCore with source, start_pos, end_pos

            Let token_type be proc match_keyword from ident
            Return proc create_token with token_type, ident, line, column
        End If

        Let is_letter_check be proc is_letter from ch
        Let is_digit_check be proc is_digit from ch
        Let is_underscore be 0

        If ch is equal to 95:
            Set is_underscore to 1
        End If

        If is_letter_check is equal to 0:
            If is_digit_check is equal to 0:
                If is_underscore is equal to 0:
                    Set end_pos to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
                    Set source to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
                    Set ident to proc string_substring from StringCore with source, start_pos, end_pos

                    Set token_type to proc match_keyword from ident
                    Return proc create_token with token_type, ident, line, column
                End If
            End If
        End If

        proc advance from lexer
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Scans the three numeric literal forms VHDL supports under one entry:
integer (3, 42), real (3.14), and based literals (16#FF#, 2#1010#).
Distinguishing them at scan time requires tracking two flags: has_dot
for the integer-vs-real distinction and has_hash for the base-literal
form. The token type is chosen on exit based on which flags fired,
not on partial state during the scan.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Captures start_pos/line/column at entry, initialises has_dot=0 and
has_hash=0. Main loop peeks each byte: on ASCII 46 (`.`) sets has_dot
if not already set (a second dot bails out — VHDL allows only one);
on ASCII 35 (`#`) sets has_hash and advances; otherwise tests
is_digit and is_hex_digit. Hex digit acceptance is enabled even
outside #..#-region because the lexer is permissive: distinguishing
"valid hex within based literal" from "stray hex" needs the base value
which is a semantic-level concern, not lexical. Exit assembles the
substring and picks token kind in priority order: based > real > int.
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_number" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan number (integer, real, or based literal)

    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let has_dot be 0
    Let has_hash be 0

    Note: Scan digits
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let ch be proc peek from lexer

        If ch is equal to 0:
            Let end_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
            Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
            Let num_str be proc string_substring from StringCore with source, start_pos, end_pos

            If has_hash is equal to 1:
                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_BASED_LITERAL, num_str, line, column
            End If

            If has_dot is equal to 1:
                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_REAL_LITERAL, num_str, line, column
            End If

            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_INTEGER_LITERAL, num_str, line, column
        End If

        Note: Check for decimal point
        If ch is equal to 46:
            If has_dot is equal to 0:
                Set has_dot to 1
                proc advance from lexer
            Otherwise:
                Set end_pos to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
                Set source to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
                Set num_str to proc string_substring from StringCore with source, start_pos, end_pos

                If has_dot is equal to 1:
                    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_REAL_LITERAL, num_str, line, column
                End If

                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_INTEGER_LITERAL, num_str, line, column
            End If
        End If

        Note: Check for based literal delimiter #
        If ch is equal to 35:
            Set has_hash to 1
            proc advance from lexer
        End If

        Note: Check for digit or hex digit
        Let is_digit_check be proc is_digit from ch
        Let is_hex_check be proc is_hex_digit from ch

        If is_digit_check is equal to 0:
            If is_hex_check is equal to 0:
                Set end_pos to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
                Set source to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
                Set num_str to proc string_substring from StringCore with source, start_pos, end_pos

                If has_hash is equal to 1:
                    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_BASED_LITERAL, num_str, line, column
                End If

                If has_dot is equal to 1:
                    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_REAL_LITERAL, num_str, line, column
                End If

                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_INTEGER_LITERAL, num_str, line, column
            End If
        End If

        proc advance from lexer
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Consumes a VHDL double-quoted string literal. VHDL string literals
can span multiple characters and represent bit vectors, character
sequences, or general string values depending on context — that
distinction is parser/semantic, not lexical. The lexer's job is to
capture the bytes between the opening and closing quote and emit
TOKEN_STRING_LITERAL with the raw payload.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads line/column at entry, advances past the opening quote (ASCII 34),
records start_pos. Main loop peeks; on EOF returns the token with
whatever was accumulated so far (silent unterminated-string tolerance —
parser will reject), on closing quote (34) captures substring before
consuming the quote, then returns TOKEN_STRING_LITERAL. No escape
handling here — VHDL strings escape `"` by doubling it, which the
current implementation does NOT process; that's a known limitation
for the lexer subset and would be fixed by an "if next char is `"`
also" check on the close-quote branch.
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_string" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan string literal (double-quoted)

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24

    Note: Skip opening quote
    proc advance from lexer

    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    Note: Scan until closing quote
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let ch be proc peek from lexer

        If ch is equal to 0:
            Let end_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
            Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
            Let str_value be proc string_substring from StringCore with source, start_pos, end_pos

            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_STRING_LITERAL, str_value, line, column
        End If

        If ch is equal to 34:
            Set end_pos to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
            Set source to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
            Set str_value to proc string_substring from StringCore with source, start_pos, end_pos

            proc advance from lexer

            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_STRING_LITERAL, str_value, line, column
        End If

        proc advance from lexer
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Consumes a single-character VHDL character literal of the form `'X'`.
The disambiguation between character literal and attribute tick
(signal'event) is the caller's job — by the time scan_character is
invoked, tokenize_next has already verified the pattern `'X'` via
two peek_ahead lookups. This routine is the strict consumer with no
re-classification.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads line/column for the token coordinates. Consumes opening
apostrophe (advance), reads the next byte (advance returns it as ch),
then peeks the closing apostrophe. On match consumes the closing
quote and emits TOKEN_CHARACTER_LITERAL with a one-byte string built
via string_from_char. Mismatch (closing != ASCII 39) returns a
TOKEN_ERROR with the literal "Invalid character literal" payload;
the parser will report the position to the user.
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_character" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan character literal (single-quoted)

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24

    Note: Skip opening apostrophe
    proc advance from lexer

    Note: Get character
    Let ch be proc advance from lexer

    Note: Check for closing apostrophe
    Let closing be proc peek from lexer

    If closing is equal to 39:
        proc advance from lexer

        Let char_str be proc string_from_char from StringCore with ch
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_CHARACTER_LITERAL, char_str, line, column
    End If

    Note: Not a valid character literal, return error
    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_ERROR, "Invalid character literal", line, column
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Main Tokenization
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level lexer driver: skip whitespace+comments, emit one token. The
two-pass structure (this routine handles comment-vs-minus disambiguation,
tokenize_next handles everything else) exists because comments share
their leading byte with the minus operator — only by peeking the byte
after the `-` can we decide between a comment skip (`--`) and emitting
TOKEN_MINUS. Putting that disambiguation inside the whitespace loop
means comments are transparent to upstream consumers.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Outer loop iterates so consecutive comments collapse into a single
skip. Each iteration first calls skip_whitespace, then peeks. EOF
returns TOKEN_EOF with empty string. ASCII 45 (`-`) triggers a
peek_ahead(1): if also 45 it's a comment (skip_comment, loop again);
otherwise emit TOKEN_MINUS. Any other byte delegates to tokenize_next
which never returns null — guarantees forward progress per call.
@End Implementation

Process called "next_token" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get next token from source

    Note: Skip whitespace and comments
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        proc skip_whitespace from lexer

        Let ch be proc peek from lexer

        Note: Check for EOF
        If ch is equal to 0:
            Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
            Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_EOF, "", line, column
        End If

        Note: Check for comment (-- )
        If ch is equal to 45:
            Let next_ch be proc peek_ahead with lexer, 1

            If next_ch is equal to 45:
                proc skip_comment from lexer
            Otherwise:
                Set line to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
                Set column to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
                proc advance from lexer
                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_MINUS, "-", line, column
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Return proc tokenize_next from lexer
        End If
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lookahead probe used wherever the lexer needs to disambiguate
multi-character operators (`<=`, `:=`, `..`, `=>`, etc.) and the
`'X'` character-literal-vs-attribute pattern. Keeping the lookahead
function separate from peek prevents adding a cursor mutation on
disambiguation paths — peek_ahead is always pure-read.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads pos (offset 8), source (0), length (32), computes peek_pos =
pos + offset (caller passes offset 1 for next-char, 2 for two-ahead).
Bounds-guards on peek_pos >= source_len returning 0; otherwise reads
the byte via string_char_at. No negative-offset handling — calls are
always with positive offsets.
@End Implementation

Process called "peek_ahead" takes lexer as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek ahead by offset characters

    Let pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let source_len be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
    Let peek_pos be pos plus offset

    If peek_pos is greater than or equal to source_len:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, peek_pos
    Return ch
End Process

@Reasoning:
The bulk dispatcher: given a single non-whitespace byte at the cursor,
decide which token type to emit. Structured in priority order:
identifier-or-keyword first (most common), then numeric literals,
then string/character literals, then multi-character operators (using
peek_ahead for disambiguation), then single-character operators and
punctuation. Unknown bytes degrade to TOKEN_ERROR rather than aborting
so a malformed source still produces a token stream the parser can
diagnose.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
First peek determines dispatch. Letters route to scan_identifier (which
fuses keyword classification), digits to scan_number, double-quote (34)
to scan_string. Apostrophe (39) splits with two-ahead lookahead: if
byte at +2 is also 39 it's a `'X'` character literal, otherwise it's
the attribute tick token. The multi-char operator block handles `<=`
(also `<>` and bare `<`), `>=`/`>`, `=>`/`=`, `:=`/`:`, `/=`/`/`,
`**`/`*`, `..`/`.`. Single-char punctuation (parens, brackets, comma,
semicolon, plus, ampersand, pipe) advance and emit directly. Final
fallback advances one byte and emits TOKEN_ERROR with "Unknown
character" payload — guarantees the cursor moves forward every call,
preventing parser-driven infinite loops on bad input.
@End Implementation

Process called "tokenize_next" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Tokenize next token (after whitespace/comments)

    Let ch be proc peek from lexer
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24

    Note: Identifier or keyword
    If proc is_letter with ch is equal to 1:
        Return proc scan_identifier from lexer
    End If

    Note: Number
    If proc is_digit with ch is equal to 1:
        Return proc scan_number from lexer
    End If

    Note: String literal
    If ch is equal to 34:
        Return proc scan_string from lexer
    End If

    Note: Character literal or attribute
    If ch is equal to 39:
        Note: Distinguish between character literal ('A') and attribute tick (signal'event)
        Note: Character literal: single quote, character, single quote
        Note: Attribute tick: single quote after identifier (handled in identifier parsing)

        Let next_ch be proc peek_ahead with lexer, 1
        Let next_next_ch be proc peek_ahead with lexer, 2

        Note: Check if this is a character literal pattern: 'X'
        If next_next_ch is equal to 39:
            Note: Pattern matches character literal
            Return proc scan_character from lexer
        Otherwise:
            Note: This is an attribute tick (')
            proc advance from lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_TICK, "'", line, column
        End If
    End If

    Note: Two-character operators
    If ch is equal to 60:
        Set next_ch to proc peek_ahead with lexer, 1

        If next_ch is equal to 61:
            proc advance from lexer
            proc advance from lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_ASSIGN, "<=", line, column
        End If

        If next_ch is equal to 62:
            proc advance from lexer
            proc advance from lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_BOX, "<>", line, column
        End If

        proc advance from lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LESS_THAN, "<", line, column
    End If

    If ch is equal to 62:
        Set next_ch to proc peek_ahead with lexer, 1

        If next_ch is equal to 61:
            proc advance from lexer
            proc advance from lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_GREATER_EQUAL, ">=", line, column
        End If

        proc advance from lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_GREATER_THAN, ">", line, column
    End If

    If ch is equal to 61:
        Set next_ch to proc peek_ahead with lexer, 1

        If next_ch is equal to 62:
            proc advance from lexer
            proc advance from lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_ARROW, "=>", line, column
        End If

        proc advance from lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_EQUAL, "=", line, column
    End If

    If ch is equal to 58:
        Set next_ch to proc peek_ahead with lexer, 1

        If next_ch is equal to 61:
            proc advance from lexer
            proc advance from lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_COLON_EQUAL, ":=", line, column
        End If

        proc advance from lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_COLON, ":", line, column
    End If

    If ch is equal to 47:
        Set next_ch to proc peek_ahead with lexer, 1

        If next_ch is equal to 61:
            proc advance from lexer
            proc advance from lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_NOT_EQUAL, "/=", line, column
        End If

        proc advance from lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_SLASH, "/", line, column
    End If

    If ch is equal to 42:
        Set next_ch to proc peek_ahead with lexer, 1

        If next_ch is equal to 42:
            proc advance from lexer
            proc advance from lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_DOUBLE_STAR, "**", line, column
        End If

        proc advance from lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_STAR, "*", line, column
    End If

    If ch is equal to 46:
        Set next_ch to proc peek_ahead with lexer, 1

        If next_ch is equal to 46:
            proc advance from lexer
            proc advance from lexer
            Return proc create_token with TOKEN_DOUBLE_DOT, "..", line, column
        End If

        proc advance from lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_DOT, ".", line, column
    End If

    Note: Single-character operators
    If ch is equal to 43:
        proc advance from lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_PLUS, "+", line, column
    End If

    If ch is equal to 38:
        proc advance from lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_AMPERSAND, "&", line, column
    End If

    If ch is equal to 124:
        proc advance from lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_PIPE, "|", line, column
    End If

    Note: Punctuation
    If ch is equal to 40:
        proc advance from lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN, "(", line, column
    End If

    If ch is equal to 41:
        proc advance from lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN, ")", line, column
    End If

    If ch is equal to 91:
        proc advance from lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET, "[", line, column
    End If

    If ch is equal to 93:
        proc advance from lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACKET, "]", line, column
    End If

    If ch is equal to 44:
        proc advance from lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_COMMA, ",", line, column
    End If

    If ch is equal to 59:
        proc advance from lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_SEMICOLON, ";", line, column
    End If

    Note: Unknown character
    proc advance from lexer
    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_ERROR, "Unknown character", line, column
End Process
